5":"1485","1484":"1484","1560":"1560","1494":"1494","1528":"1528","1515":"1515","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Blairquhan, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Blairquhan, Ayrshire, Schotland","Scotland":"Schotland"},"en":{"before 1484–1522":"before 1484–1522","1484–1522":"1484–1522","1494–Female":"1494–Deceased","1498–1528":"1498–1528","1485–1560":"1485–1560","1469–1515":"1469–1515","1469–Female":"1469–Deceased","1469":"1469","1522":"1522","about 1515":"about 1515","1498":"1498","before 1484":"before 1484","Nov 7 1485":"about 1485","1485":"1485","1484":"1484","1560":"1560","1494":"1494","1528":"1528","1515":"1515","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Blairquhan, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Blairquhan, Ayrshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Kennedy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish and Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Ceannéidigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Ceannéidigh</i>’ (from <i>ceann</i> ‘head’ + <i>éidigh</i> ‘ugly’); or from the Scottish Gaelic <b>Mac Cinnèidigh</b>, consisting of <i>mac</i> ‘son’ with an equivalent name. Compare   Canaday  ,   Cannady  ,   Cannedy  ,   Kannady  , and   Kenedy  .","History: Kennedy ancestral lands are found both in Ireland and in Scotland, where the family's medieval ancestral seat is sited on the Ayrshire coast, facing the Irish Sea. — The great-grandparents of President John Fitzgerald Kennedy (1917–63) came to North America as immigrants from Ireland in the 1840s. His paternal great-grandparents were Patrick Kennedy (1823–58), born in Dunganstown, County Wexford, Ireland, and Bridget Murphy, who was born probably in Owenduff, County Wexford, Ireland <i>c.</i> 1827; they came to Boston, MA, in 1849. His maternal great-grandparents were Thomas Fitzgerald (1823–85), who was born in Bruff, County Limerick, Ireland, and Rose Anna Cox, who was born probably in Tomregan or Kinawley, County Cavan, Ireland, <i>c.</i> 1835; they came to Boston, MA, in 1857. — An early Scottish Kennedy forebear of a quite different family was British colonial official Archibald Kennedy (1685–1763), the son of Alexander Kennedy of Craigoch, who emigrated to NY <i>c.</i> 1710."],"variants":[{"name":"Canada","meanings":["Altered form of Irish and Scottish   Kennedy  . Compare   Canaday   and   Canida  .","Spanish (<b>Cañada</b>): topographic name from <i>cañada</i> ‘glen, valley’."]},{"name":"Cannady","meanings":["Altered form of Irish and Scottish   Kennedy  . Compare   Canady  ,   Cannaday  , and   Kannady  ."]},{"name":"Cannaday","meanings":["Altered form of Irish and Scottish   Kennedy  . Compare   Canaday  ."]},{"name":"Canedy","meanings":["Altered form of Irish and Scottish   Kennedy  . Compare   Cannedy  ."]},{"name":"Cannedy","meanings":["Altered form of Irish and Scottish   Kennedy  . Compare   Canedy  ."]},{"name":"Canaday","meanings":["Altered form of Irish and Scottish   Kennedy  . Compare   Canada   and   Cannaday  ."]},{"name":"Canady","meanings":["Altered form of Irish and Scottish   Kennedy  . Compare   Canada  ,   Canaday  , and   Kanady  ."]},{"name":"Canida","meanings":["Altered form of Irish and Scottish   Kennedy  ."]},{"name":"Kanady","meanings":["Altered form of Irish and Scottish   Kennedy  . Compare   Canady  ."]},{"name":"Kannady","meanings":["Altered form of Irish and Scottish   Kennedy  . Compare   Cannady   and   Kanady  ."]}]},{"name":"Gavin","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Celtic origin, but uncertain ultimate derivation; it first appears in French sources as <i>Gauvain</i>. The name is borne in the Arthurian romances by one of the knights of the Round Table (more familiar in English versions as Sir  <b>Gawain</b> ). It was still in use in the north of England as late as the early 18th century and never died out in Scotland, whence it was reintroduced to England from the early 20th century. It is now very widely used in England, Wales, and elsewhere in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[{"name":"Gawain","meanings":["Of Celtic origin, but uncertain ultimate derivation; it first appears in French sources as <i>Gauvain</i>. The name is borne in the Arthurian romances by one of the knights of the Round Table (more familiar in English versions as Sir  <b>Gawain</b> ). It was still in use in the north of England as late as the early 18th century and never died out in Scotland, whence it was reintroduced to England from the early 20th century. It is now very widely used in England, Wales, and elsewhere in the English-speaking world."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Gavin Kennedy 5th of Blairquhan was born before 1484, in Blairquhan, Ayrshire, Scotland, his father, John Kennedy 4th of Blairquhan, was 14 and his mother, Mrs John Kennedy, was 15. He had at least 1 son with Janet Stewart. He died in 1522, in Scotland."},"et":{"before 1484–1522":"enne 1484–1522","1484–1522":"1484–1522","1494–Female":"1494–Surnud","1498–1528":"1498–1528","1485–1560":"1485–1560","1469–1515":"1469–1515","1469–Female":"1469–Surnud","1469":"1469","1522":"1522","about 1515":"umbes 1515","1498":"1498","before 1484":"enne 1484","Nov 7 1485":"umbes 1485","1485":"1485","1484":"1484","1560":"1560","1494":"1494","1528":"1528","1515":"1515","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Blairquhan, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Blairquhan, Ayrshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fi":{"before 1484–1522":"ennen vuotta 1484–1522","1484–1522":"1484–1522","1494–Female":"1494–Kuollut","1498–1528":"1498–1528","1485–1560":"1485–1560","1469–1515":"1469–1515","1469–Female":"1469–Kuollut","1469":"1469","1522":"1522","about 1515":"noin 1515","1498":"1498","before 1484":"ennen vuotta 1484","Nov 7 1485":"noin 1485","1485":"1485","1484":"1484","1560":"1560","1494":"1494","1528":"1528","1515":"1515","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Blairqu